SIMPLE: operate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Operate
<hw>Op"er*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Operated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Operating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>operatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>operari</ets> to work, fr.
<ets>opus</ets>, <ets>operis</ets>, work, labor; akin to Skr.
<ets>apas</ets>, and also to G. <ets>⟦uum⟧ben</ets> to exercise, OHG.
<ets>uoben</ets>, Icel. <ets>⟦ae⟧fa</ets>. Cf. <er>Inure</er>,
<er>Maneuver</er>, <er>Ure</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To perform a
work or labor; to exert power or strength, physical or mechanical; to
act.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To produce an appropriate physical effect; to issue
in the result designed by nature;</def> <specif>especially</specif>
<fld>(Med.)</fld>, <def>to take appropriate effect on the human
system.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To act or produce effect on the mind; to exert moral
power or influence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The virtues of private persons <qex>operate</qex> but on a
few.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A plain, convincing reason <qex>operates</qex> on the mind both of
a learned and ignorant hearer as long as they live.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>To perform some manual act upon a
human body in a methodical manner, and usually with instruments, with a
view to restore soundness or health, as in amputation, lithotomy,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To deal in stocks or any commodity with a view to
speculative profits.</def> <mark>[Brokers' Cant]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Operate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Operate
<hw>Op"er*ate</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To produce, as an
effect; to cause.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The same cause would <qex>operate</qex> a diminution of the value
of stock.</q> <rj><qau>A. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put into, or to continue in, operation or
activity; to work; <as>as, to <ex>operate</ex> a machine</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Operatical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Operatic</ent>⟦br⟧
